## Executive Summary

A critical security vulnerability has been identified in JavaScript/TypeScript's string-to-byte conversion mechanism that allows attackers to bypass Web Application Firewall (WAF) and Intrusion Detection System (IDS) protections. The vulnerability, dubbed "Ghost Bits," enables attackers to execute SQL injection, path traversal, XSS, command injection, file upload bypasses, JWT forgery, and HTTP request smuggling attacks by exploiting high-bit truncation during type conversions from UTF-16 strings to bytes.

This vulnerability affects the Node.js standard library and numerous third-party frameworks including Express, Koa, Fastify, jsonwebtoken, Multer, Sequelize, and TypeORM.

## Severity

**Critical** - CVSS:3.1/AV:N/AC:L/PR:N/UI:N/S:U/C:H/I:H/A:H (9.8)

## Affected Packages

### Standard Library
- `http` / `https` (Node.js built-in)
- `url` (Node.js built-in)
- `querystring` (Node.js built-in)
- `buffer` (Node.js built-in)

### Third-Party Frameworks
- `express` (expressjs/express) - Web framework
- `koa` (koajs/koa) - Web framework
- `fastify` (fastify/fastify) - Web framework
- `hapi` (hapijs/hapi) - Web framework
- `nest` (nestjs/nest) - Framework
- `jsonwebtoken` (auth0/node-jsonwebtoken) - JWT library
- `multer` (expressjs/multer) - File upload middleware
- `sequelize` (sequelize/sequelize) - ORM
- `typeorm` (typeorm/typeorm) - ORM
- `mongoose` (Automattic/mongoose) - MongoDB ODM

## Affected Versions

All versions

## Technical Details

### Vulnerability Mechanism

JavaScript strings are UTF-16 encoded (each character is 16 bits), while `Buffer` can hold 8-bit bytes. When converting strings to bytes using `charCodeAt() & 0xFF` or `Buffer.from(..., 'latin1')`, high bits are silently discarded:

```javascript
// Method 1: charCodeAt() & 0xFF
const ch = '\u2F58';  // 爻 (U+2F58) = 0x2F58
const byte = ch.charCodeAt(0) & 0xFF;  // Only low 8 bits: 0x58 = 'X'
// High 8 bits (0x2F) are silently lost!

// Method 2: Buffer.from(..., 'latin1')
